analysis_text:
> DETAILS
This is a Marschak-Machina triangle. It represents all lotteries over three ordered outcomes as points inside a triangle, where the top corner corresponds to certainty of the best outcome and the right corner corresponds to certainty of the worst outcome. The position of a point reflects the probabilities assigned to these outcomes, with the probability of the remaining middle outcome determined implicitly so that all probabilities sum to one. Moving within the triangle changes probability mass across outcomes while keeping payoffs fixed, so the geometry represents probability tradeoffs rather than changes in outcomes. Indifference curves drawn over the triangle summarize preferences, with straight parallel lines characterizing expected utility and systematic curvature or fanning indicating violations of it.

The implied indifference structure in this triangle is not straight and parallel, and it changes noticeably across regions. In the upper-left portion of the triangle (where the probability of the best outcome is already fairly high), the models comparisons look close to horizontal, suggesting that it primarily values the chance of the best outcome and is relatively less sensitive to how the remaining probability is split between the middle and worst outcomes. Closer to the bottom of the triangle (where the best outcome is less likely), the implied curves tilt upward from the origin, indicating that increasing the probability of the worst outcome must be compensated by a higher probability of the best outcome to keep a lottery equally attractive. Overall, the pattern is consistent with a best-outcome focused evaluation that becomes sharply downside-averse when the chance of the best outcome is not already large.
tldr_text: If the good outcome is already pretty likely, the model mostly cares about keeping that chance high; but when the good outcome isnt very likely, it becomes much more wary of increasing the chance of the bad outcome.
